FRUIT VIRUSES - ECUADOR
***********************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 30 Jun 2014
Source: Fresh Fruit Portal [edited]
http://www.freshfruitportal.com/2014/06/30/new-unreported-papaya-disease-identified-in-ecuador/?country=others


Diego Quito Avila, Ecuadorian Center for Biotechnological Research (CIBE), has identified a new virus in papaya plantations. "There is no record of this virus in global databases for any crop. There are viruses in other crops that are distantly related at a genomic level to this new species. So far, we have detected it in Ecuador. Its presence is not known in other regions of the world."

The virus was found by extracting RNA from plants that arrived for analysis of _Papaya ringspot virus_ (PRSV), which is present globally and is of great economic significance to the trade. "Besides PRSV, there was an RNA of a different size to PRSV," he said. The RNA [is] phylogenetically related to members of the genus _Umbravirus_, with a genome of between 4-5kb. "The form of transmission has not yet been determined, nor has it been determined if it causes symptoms in the plant." He said that studies were underway to find out whether it interacted with PRSV to cause severe symptoms. "We are working to find out what the risk of this virus in papayas is."

"In melons, watermelons and cucumber, we have detected and reported the melon yellow spot virus (MYSV) for the 1st time in Ecuador. This virus was detected 1st in Japan, and only reported in some Asian countries. Including MYSV in routine analysis in our region is of vital importance, as combined with other viruses, they could result in great economic losses."

In tomatillos, he said at least 3 potyviruses had been found, which were currently under investigation to determine their importance and role. "We suspect the presence of additional viruses in this crop, and we are working on determining whether it involves something new," he said.

"Additionally, for the 1st time in Ecuador we reported the _Raspberry bushy dwarf virus_ (RBDV) in commercial Castilla raspberry (_Rubus glaucus_) crops." This is one of the most common viruses in blackberries and raspberries globally. The isolate of RBDV in Ecuador has special characteristics at the genomic level which distinguishes it from isolates from other parts of the world."

"Thanks to funds provided by the International Foundation for Science (IFS), we have [also] been exploring viral diversity in plants native to the Galapagos Islands," he said.

